<TEXT>
the state labor commissioner created a board of 
inquiry thursday to investigate the tense contract negotiations at 
the daily news 
the action by labor commissioner thomas f hartnett followed the 
certification by the chairman of the state board of mediation 
hezekiah brown that a panel was necessary to interpret the 
situation at the tabloid newspaper 
a board of inquiry under state labor law has the power to 
compel both sides in a labor dispute to state their positions 
while the state cannot force the settlement of a labor dispute the 
board can make recommendations or can be a vehicle for a 
coolingoff period 
we strongly feel that this step is an unnecessary intrusion by 
the government into a private sector matter said john t sloan 
the news vice president for human resources the news is owned by 
the tribune co of chicago 
this is the first time since the labor commissioner was 
empowered to create such panels in 1941 that this step has been 
taken without a strike under way 
hartnett said the board of inquiry may be the only way to head 
off a strike 
the 10 unions at the news under the umbrella of the allied 
printing trades council requested the board because they said they 
werent getting a fair shake in the negotiations over contracts 
that expired march 30 
central to the offers the news has made have been changes in 
work rules that management says are necessary to make the paper 
profitable and enable it to invest in new plants and equipment 
the unions have said the news is bent on provoking a strike and 
wants to shut down the paper or sell it at the expense of the 
workers charges the paper denies 
sloan said the news would have to review its options including 
a possible court challenge to the board 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

