<TEXT>
in the shadow of a mausoleum that until 
recently housed the body of communist bulgarias founder 
prodemocracy protesters have erected a tent city to press for a 
quicker break with the stalinist past 
while the mausoleum still stands the embalmed body of georgi 
dimitrov was whisked away one night for cremation and burial in a 
cemetery 
the soldiers who served as honor guards outside the former 
shrine have been replaced by the mushrooming tent city of 
antigovernment protesters a gathering unthinkable even a year ago 
at least 270 people are living in more than 100 tents they 
range from young to old but most are under 40 
for residents of the selfproclaimed city of truth 
democracy has not made nearly enough inroads in the small balkan 
country now deeply polarized by the victory of the socialist party 
the former communists in junes free elections 
the elections followed the ouster last november of hardline 
leader todor zhivkov 
while many bulgarians have fled the sweltering metropolis for 
the black sea coast or the cool mountains tent city residents seem 
determined to spend the summer camped out in sofia they have 
pledged to leave only when those they see as perpetrators of 
communist sins are brought to account 
the protesters get water from a faucet in a yard nearby and 
carry buckets back to the tents food is brought by relatives or 
friends or purchased by the campers in nearby shops 
visitors from rural bulgaria gaze in wonder at the encampment 
around the oncehallowed mausoleum and the nearby socialist party 
headquarters for them it is hard to believe that icons revered 
for 45 years could fall at least so fast 
a symbolic pile of trash is the ultimate insult to the old 
system hundreds of old communist publications speeches and rule 
books are strewn around an old car plastered with defaced portraits 
of stalin lenin and other former official heroes 
bolstered by their success in securing the resignation of 
president petar mladenov earlier this month the campers showed 
little concern on monday when the government told local authorities 
to halt ethnic and political unrest 
whats to fear asked evgeni genchev a 32yearold sofia 
doctor i dont think anything really dangerous can happen to us 
but i think something really dangerous can happen to them you know 
what happened in romania 
he was referring to western criticism and a halt in aid after 
romania cracked down on antigovernment protesters in june 
bulgarias leaders really need western economic help we dont 
want this help to be given to this kind of government they are 
lying all the time genchev said 
discontent with bulgarias government and with political 
opposition groups is simmering 
sofia residents daily deplore the parliamentary stalemate and 
procedural haggling that so far have blocked the election of anyone 
to replace mladenov as president he resigned july 6 over a 
controversy about using force against antigovernment protests 
a new government cannot be formed until a president is chosen 
and bulgarians and western diplomats fear lawmakers are courting 
danger by failing to agree on leaders to fight a worsening economic 
crisis 
bulgaria has stopped paying capital and interest on its foreign 
debt of nearly 11 billion any exportable item is being sent 
abroad resulting in growing food shortages prices are expected to 
rise soon in an attempt to fill state coffers 
on tuesday hundreds of jeering demonstrators and dozens of 
honking cars blocked traffic outside the socialist party 
headquarters in support of a trade union threat to stage a general 
strike if the economic crisis is not tackled soon 
bulgarian nationalists meanwhile have shut down services in 
areas of the country heavily populated by members of the 1 
millionmember ethnic turkish minority 
the nationalists are angry that ethnic turks who suffered a 
brutal assimilation campaign under former communist leader zhivkov 
were allowed to win representation in parliament where their 
movement is the thirdstrongest faction 
the city of truth provides citizens not only with 
instruction in the relatively new art of peaceful protest but with 
comic relief 
one day this week two people donned masks of zhivkov and 
current socialist party leader alexander lilov and clowned around 
embracing mocking lilovs renunciation of zhivkovs 35year rule 
a sign on a nearby tent taunted british publisher robert 
maxwell who recently has purchased a soccer team a large share in 
a printing house and other concerns in bulgaria 
mr maxwell are you going to buy us the sign said 
