<TEXT>
a house armed services subcommittee is 
proposing a cut in the nations armed forces of 129000 troops 
with the army and air force taking the deepest reductions in the 
fiscal 1991 military budget 
the panel on military personnel and compensation on thursday 
approved a cut in the army of 68500 and the air force of 37000 
the reductions would slash 50000 soldiers from the current active 
duty forces in europe a congressional decision based on the 
lessening soviet threat 
reductions for the navy would total 20000 while the marine 
corps would lose about 4000 spots 
consistent with the house budget resolution approved on may 1 
the armed services committee is drawing up a military budget of 
283 billion 24 billion less than president bush had sought in 
january 
the action by the subcommittee was the first of several steps 
taken by various armed services panels leading up to the full 
committees crafting of a 1991 defense bill on tuesday 
the total troop reduction from the nearly 21 million troops is 
slightly higher than the 100000 approved by the senate armed 
services committee in its version of the defense bill and nearly 
four times the total of 38000 in the presidents proposed budget 
in other developments the subcommittee on military 
installations agreed to prohibit spending any defense funds on 
moving the 401st tactical wing from torrejon de ardoz spain to 
crotone italy or any other location overseas subcommittee 
chairwoman patricia schroeder dcolo said 
defense money could be used however to move the 72 f16 jet 
fighters from torrejon de ardoz to any site in the united states 
the panel also agreed to delay closing military bases while 
requiring defense secretary dick cheney to come up with an 
acceptable proposal to congress likely a commission on how 
installations can be shut down 
democrats had criticized cheneys proposed list in january as 
partisan in its selections 
the panel on seapower and strategic and critical materials 
agreed to bushs request for five ddg51 navy destroyers at a cost 
of 36 billion and his proposal of 12 billion for the 18th 
trident missilelaunching submarine 
but the panel agreed to only one of the two ssn21 seawolf 
attack submarines president bush had sought in the fiscal year 
beginning oct 1 
the seapower subcommittee was forced to cut 3 billion from the 
presidents original request of 161 billion 
on the contentious issue of strategic home porting of naval 
vessels the subcommittee failed to approve a measure that would 
have directed navy secretary h lawrence garrett iii to close the 
home port in staten island ny and impose a moratorium on 
construction at five other home ports 
the subcommittee expressed concern about acting on the issue 
before cheney completes his review of military installations 
worldwide 
among those facilities are planned home ports in everett wash 
ingleside texas pascagoula miss mobile ala and pensacola 
fla 
the panel left a final decision on the home porting issue to the 
full armed services committee 
behind closed doors the panel agreed to one of the ssn21 
seawolf attack submarines the navy had planned to buy two of the 
nuclear boats in the fiscal year beginning oct 1 at a total cost 
of 23 billion 
the panels action came two days after the general accounting 
office the investigative arm of congress recommended that 
congress slow down the 44 billion submarine program because 15 of 
the costly vessels will be under contract before critical testing 
on the lead ship has been completed 
the first submarine designed by the newport news shipbuilding 
co of virginia and the electric boat division of general 
dynamics in connecticut is estimated at 19 billion 
the navy expects the cost of subsequent submarines to decline 
averaging around 1 billion 
