<TEXT>
congress is close to making major changes in 
the way government and industry deal with oil spills since 
negotiators agreed on a bill creating a 1 billion federal oil 
spill cleanup fund 
a house and senate conference committee approved legislation 
thursday that would significantly increase oil shippers liability 
for spills create the cleanup fund and require that most tankers 
have double hulls within 20 years 
the package must still go back to the house and senate but 
supporters predicted final approval before the august congressional 
recess 
president bush is expected to sign the measure 
approval of the compromise bill came 16 months after the exxon 
valdez tanker ran aground in alaskas prince william sound and 
spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil along the states 
coastline it was the nations worst oil spill and prompted demands 
for tougher federal requirements on oil shippers and better 
preparation for responding to spills 
under the bill shippers would be liable for up to 1200 per 
gross ton of the tanker instead of the current ceiling of 150 per 
gross ton 
as an example a tanker the size of the exxon valdez under the 
new requirements would be liable to up to 115 million with 
unlimited liability if gross negligence is found to be involved 
under current law such a tanker would face only 15 million in 
legal liability 
exxon already has spent an estimated 2 billion in cleanup 
efforts as a result of the march 24 1989 spill 
other major provisions in the compromise legislation include 
creation of a 1 billion oil spill response and cleanup fund 
with the money coming from a 5centabarrel fee on both domestic 
and imported oil the fee can be used for immediate cleanup 
requirements as well as compensating for damages beyond what 
shippers are required to pay under the liability provision 
a requirement that all new tankers have double hulls and that 
most of the existing tankers be retrofitted with double hulls or 
taken out of service over the next 20 years a small number of 
tankers will be given until 2015 to have double hulls 
the coast guard has estimated that if the exxon valdez had been 
double hulled much of the 11 million gallons of oil that spilled 
into prince william sound might have been contained 
formation of regional response teams within the coast guard to 
deal with oil spills and a national response center where computers 
will hold lists of personnel and equipment that can be called upon 
after a major spill 
the legislation also calls for increased research on oil 
pollution control and requires the government to check driving 
records for alcoholrelated offenses before issuing licenses to 
operate an oil tanker 
in a stark reminder of the exxon valdez catastrophe alaskas 
congressional delegation had included in the bill a provision 
barring any tanker involved in an oil spill of more than 1 million 
gallons anywhere in the world from ever entering prince william 
sound 
the house and senate approved separate oil spill bills last 
november but progress on reconciling the measures stalled over a 
number of issues there were disagreements over whether to require 
doublehull tankers and whether the bill should be linked to an 
international treaty limiting oil spill liability it was decided 
in june not to make such a link 
with the most controversial issues resolved going into 
thursdays final meeting of the conference committee there 
remained only minor changes to be made in the legislation before it 
was approved by a voice vote 
injecting some lastminute drama rep walter jones dnc was 
successful in tacking on a moratorium on offshore oil drilling 
along the midatlantic states until further environmental studies 
can be made 
the amendment is aimed at plans by mobil corp and several 
other oil companies to drill for natural gas on leases off cape 
hatteras nc it prohibits any drilling until after oct 1 1991 
so the new environmental studies can be conducted 
rep ron marlenee rmont who opposed the amendment said he 
expects the provision to be challenged when the compromise bill 
comes up for approval in the house congressional sources said 
however they doubt the issue will derail the legislation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

