<TEXT>
junk bond financier michael milken and 
convicted stock speculator ivan boesky will be granted immunity 
from additional prosecution to get them to testify before congress 
that decision by the house energy and commerce committee on 
thursday means that nothing the two most famous figures in the wall 
street scandals of the 1980s tell to congress could be used against 
them in court 
no date has been set for their appearance before the panels 
investigations subcommittee but the committee agreed to delay 
milkens testimony until after he is sentenced for securities 
fraud now scheduled for oct 1 
the committee voted 421 to grant immunity a twothirds 
majority was needed the lone dissent came from rep joe barton 
rtexas spokesman craig murphy said the congressman does not 
believe in giving immunity to convicted felons 
boesky has agreed to extensive subcommittee staff interviews 
before his actual testimony milken has not agreed to such 
interviews said rep john dingell dmich chairman of both the 
committee and subcommittee 
milken former head of drexel burnham lambert incs highrisk 
highyield bond department pleaded guilty to six felony charges in 
april and agreed to pay 600 million to settle the biggest 
financial fraud case against an individual he faces up to 28 years 
in prison at sentencing in new york 
boesky once a leading speculator in the stocks of companies 
that were potential takeover targets pleaded guilty to one count 
of conspiracy to violate securities laws and was released april 4 
after serving about twothirds of a threeyear prison sentence 
the committees vote ended a tug of war between the justice 
department which does not want milken to testify before he is 
sentenced and dingell the powerful committee chairman 
previously dingell wanted to hear from milken before the end of 
the current congressional session expected sometime in early 
october 
justice department sources who asked not to be identified said 
prosecutors were concerned milken could withdraw his guilty plea 
after being immunized making it difficult if not impossible 
for any prosecution to continue 
dingell said the us attorneys office asked the subcommittee 
to withhold taking milkens testimony until after the sentencing 
and congressional sources said dingell agreed to the delay 
in a memo to committee members circulated before the vote 
dingell noted that the recent reversal of some of the charges 
against irancontra figure oliver north raised concerns about 
immunized testimony 
a federal appeals court in washington ruled that congressional 
testimony like that given by north in the summer of 1987 could 
unfairly prejudice a defendants trial 
a spokesman for milken said of course we will testify when 
they ask him to testify 
milken was linked to a large insider trading network headed by 
boesky 
dingell wants to know about some 500 limited partnerships set 
up by milken and the drexel junk bond department that bought 
significant stakes in hot junk bond issues underwritten by drexel 
before they were made available to the public 
critics say the activity drove up the price of those issues at 
the expense of drexel customers but the transactions legality has 
never been resolved 
milken was called to testify before the investigations 
subcommittee in 1988 but invoked his fifth amendment right against 
possible selfincrimination 
a subpoena also was authorized at that time for boesky but never 
acted upon pending the outcome of the milken probe 
