<TEXT>
two cosmonauts have repaired a balky hatch that 
bedeviled them and dangerously prolonged a previous spacewalk 
earlier this month according to soviet news reports 
anatoly solovyov and alexander balandin also removed and stowed 
handrails during the threehour 31minute spacewalk thursday 
they had affixed the handrails to the outside of the spacecraft 
during a july 17 excursion to repair torn thermal insulation on the 
outside of their soyuz tm9 capsule the tass news agency said 
tass said ground controllers indicated that human error at the 
start of the previous spacewalk caused the hatch problem the 
cosmonauts had opened the hatch before the airlock was completely 
depressurized and it swung outward with such force that a key 
joint was damaged 
solovyev and balandin began their spacewalk thursday by again 
trying to close the hatch which was less than an inch ajar tass 
said 
they made little progress however and ground controllers told 
them to relax and work on stowing the ladderlike handrails which 
were left behind july 17 when solovyev and balandin had to rush 
back inside the spacecraft because their oxygen was running low 
the handrails could have posed a problem when the capsule 
separated from the mir space station for the cosmonauts return 
voyage home 
tass said ground controllers studied a televised picture of the 
hatch and officials at the soviet mission control center in 
kaliningrad outside moscow recommended how to repair the joint 
tass said the cosmonauts then were able to close the hatch 
completely 
they pressurized the airlock and removed their space suits tass 
said 
the evening television newscast vremya reported that ground 
controllers would be monitoring the pressure in the airlock to make 
sure the outside hatch had sealed properly 
the balky hatch was the latest in a series of problems to 
trouble the cosmonauts sixmonth mission 
tass focused on its accomplishments completing 506 of 520 
scientific experiments photographing 84 million square miles of 
the earths surface and growing 23 crystals in the weightless 
environment of space the report said each crystal was worth 1 
million 
the cosmonauts who have been in space since feb 11 are 
scheduled to return home on aug 9 a replacement crew is to be 
launched aug 1 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

