a british colonial court today convicted five 
prodemocracy activists of using a megaphone and collecting money 
without a permit in a case that has been called a show trial to 
suppress political activism 
critics said the verdict was another example of britain 
kowtowing to communist china which takes control of the colony in 
1997 when britains 99year lease runs out 
magistrate betty kwan told a packed courtroom that using 
megaphones during political demonstrations was not necessary or 
justified and fined the five the equivalent of about 20 each 
the defendants four men and one woman said they would appeal 
if they lose they said they would refuse the fine and risk prison 
we are fully prepared for the consequences said yeung sum 
a professor at hong kong university and one of the defendants 
he accused the british colonial government of trying to 
silence those who express their political opinions in a peaceful 
and orderly manner 
yeung lawyer albert ho labor union leader lau chinshek 
teacher lee wingtat and christian worker wong pikwan the woman 
in the group are central committee members of the united democrats 
of hong kong a political party that was formed in april to promote 
democracy in hong kong 
they along with political activist tsang kimshing were 
prosecuted under a 1933 law forbidding the use of bullhorns the 
law is rarely invoked and widely ignored by teachers and tour 
guides who use bullhorns daily 
tsang who is not a leader of the united democrats party was 
acquitted 
the group held a peaceful sitin at the star ferry terminal in 
february and called for greater protection of human rights in hong 
kong they collected donations and gave speeches through a 
megaphone 
police charged the group in late may two weeks before the 
anniversary of the bloody crackdown on a movement for democracy in 
china on june 4 about 100000 people took to the streets in hong 
kong that day to commemorate the crackdown 
several us congressmen and petra kelly leader of west 
germanys green party have expressed concern about the case 
amnesty international the londonbased human rights 
organization said it would adopt the defendants as prisoners of 
conscience if they are imprisoned 
fridays case marks the third time in the last 10 months that 
the hong kong government has prosecuted political activists 
many people in hong kong worry that once china takes control of 
the territory it will break its promise to maintain hong kongs 
freewheeling economic and social system for 50 years 
many also have begun to doubt britains commitment to supporting 
hong kong up to 1997 
over the past few months the colonial government has barred 
prominent chinese dissidents from entering hong kong censored 
films critical of china and turned away the goddess of democracy 
radio ship which wanted to beam prodemocracy messages to mainland 
china 
hong kong government officials have publicly denied that the 
government is trying to suppress political activism 
but in a confidential letter written to chinese authorities late 
last year british colonial official william ehrman stressed that 
britain would not allow hong kong to be used as a base for 
subversive activities 
