<TEXT>
a usfunded project to 
study tigers in the wild has been canceled by a state official in 
southern india experts say the move threatens indias attempts to 
save its share of the worlds biggest cat 
the minister of forests for karnataka also is trying to transfer 
an internationally recognized forest service officer involved in 
the research 
minister basappa basavalingappa said he wants a friend to 
replace forest service officer km chinnappa who was awarded a 
medal for wildlife conservation in 1989 by the new york zoological 
society 
observers in bangalore the state capital say political motives 
were behind the ministers decision 
basavalingappa said he stopped the indous tiger project 
funded by a 90000 grant from the us fish and wildlife service 
because it interferes with nature 
if nature wants tigers to die out who are we to save them 
he said in an interview have you ever heard a tiger complain 
an increasing number of rural indians oppose the countrys 
system of national parks they accuse the government of depriving 
them of grazing land a growing number of deaths from encounters 
with lions tigers and elephants has fueled this anger last year 
at least 150 people were killed by wild animals 
ironically the goal of the canceled project was to alleviate 
this tension 
the project sought to answer such questions as how much land 
tigers need how much prey they eat and how they mate according to 
its director ku karanth who heads the indian center for 
wildlife studies in mysore also in karnataka 
armed with this knowledge forest officers could better manage 
tigers moving the cats from an overpopulated reserve to a less 
crowded one or in extreme cases culling tigers he said 
karanth said he had hoped his research could be used by indias 
project tiger a string of 18 tiger reserves established in 1973 
although they have gotten high marks for protecting tigers the 
reserves have been criticized for their failure to adequately 
manage the tiger population 
karanth said he would fight the ministers order in court but 
was not optimistic about winning 
