<TEXT>
economic activity last year was significantly 
weaker than previously thought because the government badly 
overestimated the strength in personal incomes the commerce 
department said today 
the department said the broadest measure of economic health 
the gross national product grew just 25 percent in 1989 instead 
of the 3 percent previously estimated 
that put economic growth at its slowest pace since a drop of 25 
percent in the recession year of 1982 
the government also put out new estimates for growth in 1988 and 
1987 it said the gnp grew 45 percent in 1988 just slightly above 
the 44 percent previously estimated it put growth in 1987 at 34 
percent down from a 37 percent previous estimate 
but it was the 1989 change that was likely to raise eyebrows 
the government blamed its mistake on overestimating by 579 
billion the amount americans earned in wages and salaries 
the initial estimate is based on a partial sample of businesses 
while the revision takes into account more complete data gathered 
from the countrys roughly 6 million businesses 
the more complete data is used when the government makes its 
onceayear revisions to gnp data every july 
while the full details of the commerce department revisions were 
made public only today the information was made available earlier 
to economists at the office and management and budget 
the big drop in incomes which also would affect taxes was a 
major factor behind the administrations dramatic increase in the 
budget deficit it boosted the 1991 deficit to 169 billion up 
from an estimate of 1005 billion made last january 
