<TEXT>
east germanys secondbiggest political party 
withdrew its threat to resign from the government today averting a 
political crisis over the process of german unification 
the leftleaning social democrats threatened tuesday to leave 
the coalition government of prime minister lothar de maiziere today 
unless a dispute over united german elections was reached 
the liberal party resigned tuesday over the dispute with 
compromise now in sight on the political feud the liberals planned 
to meet to reconsider their decision 
meanwhile social democrat party chief wolfgang thierse said his 
party would remain in de maizieres government even though a key 
difference remained over how german elections should be held 
the social democrats and the conservative christian demcrats of 
de maiziere the biggest party in east germany agree that the two 
german nations will vote as a single electorate for a united 
parliament on dec 2 
under that plan east germany would dissolve itself dec 1 
the christian democrats and several smaller political parties 
had demanded that east germany remain a nation at the time of 
balloting so that two elections could be held that would give 
smaller parties a better chance of winning seats in parliament 
de maiziere and the christian democrats backed down from that 
demand in recent days 
however disagreement still exists over what percentage of the 
vote a party must get to be represented in parliament 
under west german law parties need 5 percent of the vote to be 
represented in parliament no minimum is required in east germany 
the social democrats want the 5 percent limit while the 
christian democrats and several smaller parties sought to lower it 
de maiziere has said special accomodations should be made to 
ensure that smaller east german parties have a chance to be 
represented in a big new allgerman parliament 
the social democrats in both east and west germany believe the 
lower limit would hurt them by allowing smaller leftist groups to 
get in parliament and splinter the leftleaning vote 
under one proposed compromise smaller parties could run on the 
ballots of larger parties that would allow allied parties to share 
ballot space 
that could hurt the east german communists who countrys no 3 
party because they have no allies 
under another idea the 5 percent limit would be mandated for 
each nation rather than germany as a whole 
that means an east german party would only have to win 5 percent 
of the vote in what is now east germany rather than 5 percent of 
the total vote 
another idea would allow any party with 5 percent of the vote in 
each of the 11 individual states in west germany and five in east 
germany to win representation 
the complicated argument that centered essentially on whether 
east germany should dissolve one day before or immediately after 
elections was basically political manuevering by parties seeking 
the most favorable election conditions 
there was much speculation that west german chancellor helmut 
kohl who longs to be leader of a unified germany was prodding de 
maiziere into insisting on separate elections to boost the west 
german leaders chances 
</TEXT>
