<TEXT>
the united states flying 
nuclear arms command post is no longer in the air 24 hours a day 
the strategic air command said today 
in a budgetcutting move that recognizes thawing superpower 
relations sac scaled back flights for the operation known as 
looking glass this week of the mission that had flown 
continuously since 1961 officials said 
sac said it modified the looking glass mission by putting the 
airplanes on ground alert and flying them randomly a few times each 
week 
the last of the 24houraday flights ended at 228 pm cdt 
tuesday said lt col george peck a sac spokesman 
in this time of budget crunch it was the right thing to do 
peck said 
it makes good sense to put it on an alert status instead of 
constantly in the air where the world situation is such that 
keeping continuously airborne is perhaps not as critical as in the 
past he said 
looking glass had flown continuously since feb 2 1961 
sac expects the change to save about 18 million in the 1991 
fiscal year that begins oct 1 peck said about 23 million should 
be saved the following year he said most of the savings will come 
from reduced fuel and maintenance costs he said 
the mission is dubbed looking glass because it mirrors the 
capability of sacs underground command center it would perform 
the command and control functions if something happened to the sac 
headquarters at offutt air force base near omaha 
the roles and responsibilities of the looking glass have not 
changed only the alert posture a sac statement said 
sac maintains the capability to launch the looking glass into 
a continuous airborne alert posture within minutes should strategic 
or tactical warning warrant 
looking glass flights include a crew of 31 three who operate 
the plane and 28 who work in the airborne command center including 
an air force general peck said 
now the crew will in a building nearby when the looking glass 
flight is not in the air he said 
recent changes in eastern europe were not directly responsible 
for the decision to modify the roundtheclock flights but world 
events contributed to the decision peck said 
improved us intelligence capabilities and the resulting 
increased warning time of any attack also were factors in the 
decision to change looking glass he said 
