<TEXT>
thawing superpower relations 
and a tight budget have clipped the wings of the nations flying 
nuclear command which is no longer in the air around the clock 
officials said friday 
the looking glass mission which had flown continuously for 
29 years was scaled back tuesday in a budgetcutting move that 
recognizes improved superpower relations the strategic air command 
announced friday 
the missions ec135 aircraft are on ground alert and will be 
flown randomly a few times a week 
in this time of budget crunch it was the right thing to do 
said lt col george peck a sac spokesman 
the world situation is such that keeping continuously airborne 
is perhaps not as critical as in the past 
sac expects the change to save about 18 million in the 1991 
fiscal year and about 23 million the following year said peck 
most of the savings will come from reduced fuel and maintenance 
the mission is dubbed looking glass because it mirrors the 
capability of sacs underground command center it would perform 
the command and control functions if something happened to the sac 
headquarters at offutt air force base near omaha 
sac maintains the capability to launch the looking glass into 
a continuous airborne alert posture within minutes should strategic 
or tactical warning warrant the command said in a statement 
flights include a crew of 31 three who operate the plane and 28 
who work in the airborne command center including an air force 
general peck said the planes fly a changing flight pattern over 
the continental united states 
the number of crews wont be cut he said 
improved us intelligence capabilities and the resulting 
increased warning time of any attack also contributed to the 
cutback he said 
</TEXT>
