<TEXT>
the government rewrote a slice of economic 
history on friday reporting that the total economy grew at a 
slower pace last year than previously thought 
the commerce department said the gross national product the 
nations broadest measure of economic health grew by 25 percent 
in 1989 instead of the 3 percent growth rate estimated earlier 
that put growth at its slowest pace since the recession year of 
1982 when the gnp actually shrank by 25 percent 
government statisticians blamed the error on mistakes made in 
estimating wages and salaries which were overstated by 579 
billion for 1989 
the correction changed not only the governments economic 
estimates but also its forecast for tax revenues over the next 
several years the office of management and budget was forced to 
slash its estimate for tax revenues by 1955 billion over the next 
five years 
the drop in expected tax revenues along with the weaker economic 
growth were two major factors forcing president bush to reverse his 
stand on taxes as part of negotiations with congress to come up 
with an acceptable deficit reduction plan 
while the commerce departments initial assessment of wages is 
based on a partial sample of businesses the july update takes into 
account more complete data gathered from the countrys roughly 6 
million businesses 
the annual economic revisions also made somewhat smaller changes 
for growth in 1988 and 1987 gnp growth for 1988 was put at 45 
percent up slightly from an earlier 44 percent estimate growth 
for 1987 was revised down to 34 percent from 37 percent 
the department also revised its estimates for quarterly economic 
growth over the past three years for 1989 gnp growth rates were 
revised down for every quarter with the biggest change occurring in 
the fourth quarter which saw growth drop from 11 percent to a 
barely noticeable 03 percent 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

