banned sales of new threewheel atvs restricted marketing of 
larger fourwheelers to adults and required age restriction 
labeling on vehicles and notices in dealerships 
it is virtually impossible for a consumer to visit an atv 
dealership and not be made aware of appropriate age recommendations 
and safe use information said howard p willens an attorney 
representing atv makers 
cpsc chairwoman jacqueline jonessmith defended the accord 
saying it struck a balance between allowing consumers the freedom 
to purchase adultsized atvs while at the same time providing 
consumers with protection against the risks associated with atvs 
however recent government and consumer studies have shown 
dealers routinely violate the agreement 
i do not mean to belittle the efforts of the cpsc said sen 
joseph lieberman dconn a member of governmental affairs panel 
nevertheless the number of deaths and injuries from atvs remains 
unacceptably high and children under 16 still account for nearly 
40 percent of those hurt or killed 
anne graham a commissioner who has opposed most cpsc decisions 
regarding atvs said the government must do more to get children 
off adultsized atvs including considering a ban 
these machines are not bought by children said willens 
arguing that federal or state action to ban the atvs would be 
improper 
willens insisted that a subsequent letter of agreement with the 
cpsc regarding monitoring and dealer discipline would ensure 
greater compliance 
two consumer groups the consumer federation of america and us 
public interest research group said it had submitted a petition to 
the cpsc that would close gaps in the current accord 
the organizations recommended the agency institute a permanent 
ban on threewheel atvs a ban on atv sales to children a 
mandatory requirement for atv lateral stability and a refund 
program to consumers for atvs purchased for children 
willens said manufacturers would resist any refund program 
</TEXT>
