<TEXT>
radioactive gas was released from a nuclear 
reactor early friday shortly after the unit at a power plant was 
shut down philadelphia electric co announced 
the 10minute release from unit 3 was well below limits for the 
plant and didnt endanger the public or workers at the peach 
bottom plant near the pennsylvaniamaryland line about 40 miles 
west of philadelphia officials said 
philadelphia electric declared an unusual event at the plant 
the lowest of four classifications of nuclear power plant 
emergencies 
unit 3 had been working at full power when it was shut down at 
403 am because of low suction in the units steam condenser 
philadelphia electric said 
during the shutdown the operators declared an unusual event at 
538 am because of a momentary increase in radiation levels in an 
internal gas filtering system the unusual event ended at 6 am 
the utility said no radiation was released up to then 
the gas release happened after the shutdown as plant operators 
were trying to restore suction in the steam condenser philadelphia 
electric said 
the release consisted primarily of inert gases such as xenon and 
krypton which dont react with other chemicals said nuclear 
regulatory commission spokesman karl abraham such gases are 
normally dispersed in the atmosphere abraham said 
the radioactivity from such a release is usually too low to 
measure he said 
unit 3 will remain shut down while workers do maintenance said 
utility spokesman neil mcdermott 
theyve been waiting for an opportunity to work on some 
systems and this is it mcdermott said none of the work is 
safetyrelated 
while the 1055megawatt reactor is shut down its twin unit 2 
is expected to continue working at 100 percent output mcdermott 
said 
the middle of summer is a time of peak demand for electricity in 
the philadelphia area mcdermott said the loss of unit 3 would 
obviously make conditions a little tighter depending on the 
weather 
abraham said nrc resident inspectors at the plant would pursue a 
routine followup on the shutdown and gas release while 
philadelphia electric carries out its own investigation 
in addition to the nrc the utility said it reported the release 
to pennsylvania maryland and york county officials 
 
</TEXT>
