the senate has given final parliamentary 
approval to legislation allowing the transfer of governmentowned 
industries to private investors that accounts for 80 percent of 
polish industries 
the senate voted 607 with two abstentions thursday to approve 
the law as passed by the sejm or lower house of parliament on 
july 13 
the senate offered no amendments to the legislation it adopted 
a resolution calling for quick work by the solidarityled 
government to prepare regulations for implementing it 
although privatization is considered crucial to the effort to 
create a capitalist system from the centralized socialist economy 
controversy over how the heavily monopolized and often outmoded 
stateowned industries should be put into private hands delayed 
passage of the legislation for months 
none of the 7600 stateowned industries will be considered 
offlimits to privatization it is expected that only about a dozen 
of the major factories will be privatized the first year although 
the sale or lease of small stateowned shops restaurants and 
services are progressing more quickly 
all citizens are to be given bonds that can be exchanged for 
company stocks allowing even the estimated 65 percent of polish 
families with no savings to participate 
there is widespread concern that economically depressed poland 
will be bought out by westerners seeking less expensive 
properties in central europe this is directed most strongly at 
neighboring germany 
in a reflection of this concern the sejm voted friday to bar 
the sale of governmentowned real estate to nonpoles the vote was 
224136 with seven abstentions 
the law does not apply to privately owned land which currently 
can be sold to foreigners with the permission of the interior 
ministry 
the threat to poland that could result from wholesale land 
purchases by foreigners has stirred concern private land now sells 
for 15 per square yard in the warsaw area 
the envisioned economic might of a united germany has coupled 
with vivid memories of its 1939 military invasion to focus distrust 
on germans 
