<TEXT>
president bush has decided against 
intervening in the planned acquisition by a japanese corporation of 
an american firm semigas systems inc that makes equipment used 
in manufacturing semiconductors the white house announced friday 
the decision follows an administration investigation of whether 
the sale of company to nippon sanso kk posed a threat to us 
security interests and drew an immediate angry response from 
executives of sematech the federally financed research consortium 
that links several important us semiconductor companies 
the parent company of semigas hercules inc of wilmington 
del in april announced its intention to sell the subidiary to 
nippon sanso for 23 million 
semigas designs assembles and installs gas systems used in 
making computer chips which must be manufactured in superclean 
environments 
weve worked with a leading american firm to develop leading 
technology and then to have that technology fall into the hands of 
a foreign competitor doesnt sit very well with us said miller 
bonner a spokesman for sematech in austin texas 
bonner said sematech also feared the sale would give the 
japanese company confidential information held by the 14 american 
computer company partners that make up the consortium 
white house deputy press secretary alixe glen said bush based 
his decision on the results of an investigation by the committee on 
foreign investment in the united states chaired by treasury 
secretary nicholas f brady 
that panel investigated national security concerns relating to 
the possible acquisition ms glen said 
the investigation was carried out under the exonflorio 
provision of the defense production act which allows the president 
to prohibit or suspend foreign acquisitions of us businesses that 
threaten national security 
if the deal goes through sematech will not allow semigas 
employees on the premises and the consortium will use every legal 
means to protect our intellectual property 
we sort of feel like were in an economic war right now he 
said 
bonner said sematech tried to block the proposed sale saying it 
would breach national security or run afoul of antitrust laws 
why would we want to develop leading world class technology 
only to sell it to a foreign competitor its very ironic that we 
get half of our funding from the department of defense and then we 
get a ruling like this he said 
the company receives about 100 million a year from the defense 
department 
</TEXT>
