<TEXT>
leukemia patient allison atlas whose 
unsuccessful quest for a perfectly matched bonemarrow donor drew 
50000 wouldbe contributors underwent tests friday for a possible 
transplant from her mother 
miss atlas 20 was admitted to the transplant floor of the fred 
hutchinson cancer research center on thursday center spokeswoman 
susan edmonds said friday 
the first step in such a transplant a week of chemotherapy and 
radiation to destroy the diseased marrow will not begin until a 
date has been set which might happen later friday edmonds said 
there have been no procedures done just some testing to 
determine miss atlas condition edmonds said 
simon atlas a cousin of miss atlas father said friday in new 
york that the chemotherapy and radiation could begin monday with 
the transplant performed early the following week 
relatives are uneasy he said but miss atlas seems to be 
pretty cool 
i spoke to her the night before shes anxious to get it done 
she wants to get on with her life atlas said she really feels 
confident its going to work its just remarkable how positive her 
attitude is 
the bethesda md woman was a student at new york university 
until she became ill last year she said last week she had decided 
to undergo a transplant of her mothers marrow while she is strong 
enough for the procedure 
arline atlass marrow matches four out of six antigens or cell 
identifiers in her daughters marrow 
with miss atlass type of leukemia doctors say there is a 60 
percent survival rate with a transplant if theres a sixantigen 
match the survival rate is even lower without a perfect match 
but without a transplant the disease is 100 percent fatal 
miss atlas is in an extremely sterile environment said edmonds 
as is the case with all bone marrow patients 
wellwishers can send cards balloons and little animals 
but she cannot receive flowers or plants said simon atlas her 
room is divided by a clear plastic curtain so she and her family 
are separated but can see each other and talk he said 
bloodproducing marrow is a key element in the bodys immune 
system and transplant recipients are extremely vulnerable to 
infection immediately after the procedure before the new marrow 
begins functioning 
a campaign launched last fall by miss atlas family and a 
support group friends of allison prompted 50000 people in the 
united states and israel to take blood tests to determine if they 
were perfect donors it also raised 3 million for processing the 
samples 
ten patients found perfectly matched donors as a result of the 
flood of new listings with the national marrow donor program but 
miss atlas was not among them 
mrs atlas had been a fallback all along simon atlas said 
earlier this week shes not a perfect match obviously or we 
would have used her at the outset 
if a perfect match is found up to the moment of transplant we 
would use it he said 
marrow from mrs atlas will be given to her daughter in a 
transfusion a procedure that takes two to three hours two to 
three weeks after the transplant doctors watch for an increase in 
white blood cells a sign that the transplant has taken 
in leukemia a form of cancer white blood cells multiply 
uncontrollably bone marrow produces blood and doctors can combat 
the cancer by replacing the diseased marrow with healthy tissue 
</TEXT>
