<TEXT>
avianca airlines announced friday it was willing 
to pay 75000 each to survivors or relatives of victims of the 
crash of flight 52 without requiring them to relinquish their 
rights to further claims 
seventythree people died and 85 were injured in the jan 25 
crash of the boeing 707 on long island during an approach to 
kennedy airport after a flight from colombia 
attorneys for the victims hailed the offer as unprecedented and 
generous 
they were smart and did what was morally correct said marc 
s moller who represents 45 of the crash victims 
this is a great humanitarian gesture said lawyer robert a 
solomon who filed a 100 million lawsuit against avianca on behalf 
of a man and his young son 
the proposal was made by an attorney for avianca george 
tompkins during a hearing before us district judge thomas c 
platt on civil lawsuits filed against the airline in the tragedy 
so far about 100 civil lawsuits have been filed against avianca 
in the crash so the offer would cost the airline at least 75 
million 
under the terms of the warsaw convention governing international 
aviation aircrash victims awards are generally limited to 
75000 unless willful misconduct by the airline is proven 
moller said that in the past airlines had paid out settlement 
money only after they had been ordered to do so by a court 
following the resolutions of often lengthy lawsuits 
moller said he would proceed with the civil lawsuits against the 
airline 
under the avianca proposal the airline also would continue to 
pay survivors medical expenses at least until the end of the year 
subtracted from the lump sum would be payments already made to 
the families 2500 to each survivor plus a 1500 monthly 
livingexpense allotment paid for the last several months 
generally solomon said payments are offered only as 
settlements in which the plaintiff agrees to drop any future legal 
action 
my client will be very pleased with this offer because they 
need the money said kenneth p nolan whose firm represents 
about two dozen families of crash victims 
he called the avianca offer generous and fair but said 
he believed many of his clients would eventually receive much more 
compensation its a good first step he said 
in addition to the action against avianca at least 12 
passengers injured in the crash have sued the federal aviation 
administration maintaining that air traffic controllers failed to 
insure a safe flight for the jetliner 
the plane crashed on a wooded hillside near cove neck ny 
about 20 miles east of new york city after running out of fuel 
under the terms of the avianca offer the us government would 
have to acknowledge that in making the payments the airline does 
not abandon its right to sue the federal government to recoup the 
payments 
