<TEXT>
a former cia agent who helped coordinate the contra 
supply effort in central america testified friday that planes were 
so illequipped they used ordinary fuzz busters to detect enemy 
radar 
felix rodriguez testimony came in the trial of a federal damage 
lawsuit by the family of william sawyer jr and eugene hasenfus 
the sole survivor of the october 1986 crash in nicaragua that 
helped unravel the irancontra affair 
hasenfus and the family of sawyer who died when sandinistas 
shot down the c123 carrying supplies to the nicaraguan rebels 
claim retired air force gen richard secord and miamibased 
southern air transport were their true employers misrepresented 
the mission and skimped on safety equipment 
rodriguez testified that when he left the operation in june 1986 
he brought thenwhite house aide oliver north a letter from crewmen 
complaining their navigational equipment was inadequate 
they hit a tree in costa rica because they were off course 
rodriguez said they had quite a lot of maintenance problems in 
the beginning 
over the strong objections of southern air attorneys rodriguez 
was allowed to testify about the primitive nature of the equipment 
he said the only radar detection devices aboard were radio shack 
fuzz busters designed to help drivers spot police cars on the 
highway 
under crossexamination rodriguez said that by september 1986 
before the crash he was told the equipment had improved 
rodriguez said he began helping the contra supply operation at 
norths request but left because his top priority was helping the 
el salvador air force fight leftist guerrillas 
the former agent who left the cia in 1976 is credited with 
capturing cuban leader fidel castros close ally ernesto che 
guevara in bolivia and was a veteran of the bay of pigs invasion in 
1961 
hasenfus attorneys also presented a deposition by richard gadd 
who helped set up the supply operation in which gadd said secord 
directed the funds and made policy decisions in the enterprise 
corporate air services was used as a front to hide the 
involvement of southern air which was once owned by the cia and 
continued to do contract work for the us government gadd said 
he and southern air president william langton decided the effort 
should be treated as a clandestine or covert activity so the 
media could not attempt to trace it back to the owners and the 
united states government the deposition said 
secord denies the connection and says he never met hasenfus or 
sawyer 
southern air has denied involvement with the hasenfus flight and 
claims hasenfus and sawyer worked for corporate air services a 
separate company 
after the crash the reagan administration acknowledged that 
money from iran arms sales was diverted to the contras despite a 
congressional ban on us military aid to the rebels 
attorneys for hasenfus of marinette wis and sawyers family 
of magnolia ark have submitted a preliminary estimate of of 34 
million in damages including expenses caused by the crash and lost 
income 
secord pleaded guilty nov 8 1989 to lying to congressional 
investigators when he said he wasnt aware of any money that went 
to norths benefit from the maze of companies he used in the 
irancontra affair he was sentenced to two years probation 
</TEXT>
