prosecutors on friday dropped all charges against 
a student accused of publishing a computer program stolen from a 
ninestate 911 emergency network in an underground electronic 
newsletter attorneys said 
craig neidorf of chesterfield mo a member of a computer 
hacker network known as the legion of doom was assigned to a 
threeyear pretrial diversion program similar to probation said 
assistant us attorney william cook 
neidorf faced 10 counts of wire fraud receiving stolen goods 
and interstate transportation of stolen goods cook said had he 
been convicted he could have faced up to 31 years in prison and 
122000 in fines 
the 20yearold prelaw student at the university of missouri 
was indicted in february in the theft a year before of the 
atlantabased bellsouth corp computer program that controlled 911 
emergency calls to police fire ambulance and emergency services 
the program handled 911 calls in alabama mississippi georgia 
tennessee kentucky louisiana north and south carolina and 
florida 
much of the computer program that prosecutors originally 
believed was stolen was actually public property which prompted 
prosecutors to drop the charges cook said 
the case was heard in us district court in chicago because the 
newsletter was published on a computer bulletin board in lockport 
ill prosecutors said 
prosecutors said legion of doom members used their computers to 
tap into the 911 system and copy the program they then published 
the information in phrack an underground electronic newsletter 
neidorf had published since he was 16 for computer freaks and 
hackers he said 
emergency telephone service was not interrupted during or 
because of the breakin although the hackers threatened the 
networks operation when they breached its security codes cook 
said 
he was just doing this to put it into his newsletter to say 
see what i got cook said it was just for ego gratification 
an ego trip 
neidorfs attorney sheldon zenner said hes happy prosecutors 
dropped the case 
we are just grateful that the us attorneys office took the 
evidence into consideration zenner said 
