<TEXT>
washington ap equals sixteen months after the exxon valdez 
disaster house and senate negotiators approved legislation 
thursday raising liability limits for oil shippers and creating a 
1 billion federal fund to clean up spills immediately 
the legislation now goes to the two chambers for final approval 
supporters said they hoped it would be ready for president bushs 
signature before congress august recess 
the bill also requires the phasing out of most singlehulled oil 
tankers over the next 20 years and the creation of regional coast 
guard strike teams to improve responses to serious tanker accidents 
the tougher requirements were the direct result of the nations 
worst oil spill on march 24 1989 when the exxon valdez ran 
aground in alaskas prince william sound the spill tarnished 
hundreds of miles of shoreline shores and devastated marine life 
exxon already has spent an estimated 2 billion in cleanup 
efforts 
the legislation agreed to thursday by a housesenate conference 
committee significantly broadens liability for shippers involved in 
an oil spill raising the liability ceilings from 150 to 1200 
per gross ton 
as a result the largest supertankers would face maximum 
liabilities under federal law of more than 240 million if gross 
negligence is involved in a spill liability would be unlimited 
under the legislation 
the house and the senate had approved separate versions of the 
bill in november progress stalled for months as negotiators tried 
to resolve differences especially over the doublehull issue and 
whether to limit industry liability in line with a proposed 
international treaty 
over the last two months the conferees resolved the treaty 
issue and settled on requiring doublehull tankers for virtually 
all of the tanker fleet by the year 2010 a few tankers would be 
given an additional five years to comply 
the coast guard has estimated that if the exxon valdez had been 
double hulled much of the 11 million gallons of oil that spilled 
into prince william sound might have been contained 
with the most controversial issues resolved going into 
thursdays final meeting of the conference committee there 
remained only minor changes to be made in the bill before it was 
approved by a voice vote 
rep walter jones dnc injected some lastminute drama into 
the proceedings however when he introduced minutes before a final 
vote an amendment aimed at blocking for a time anyway plans by 
mobil corp to drill for natural gas 40 miles off the coast of 
cape hatteras nc 
the measure was attacked by oil state congressmen but won 
approval among jones house colleagues it was not opposed by the 
senate and was written into the bill jones amendment calls for no 
drilling until oct 1 1991 so a scientific panel could further 
examine the environmental impact 
this is a pure and simple moratorium declared rep ron 
marlenee rmont he said the provision would be challenged when 
the legislation goes back for final consideration in the house 
congressional sources said its doubtful that it would derail the 
bill 
the cornerstone of the legislation remains the 1 billion 
federal fund to pay for oil spill cleanups and reimburse injured 
parties for damages the oil industry since last january has been 
paying 5 cents per barrel of oil into the fund 
while the higher liability requirements and the federal fund 
vastly increases the money that would be available after a spill 
the amounts still are far below what the exxon valdez spill is 
expected to cost 2 billion for the company alone with the job 
still unfinished 
other provisions 
creation of a national oil spill response unit under the coast 
guard where computers will hold lists of personnel and equipment 
that can be called upon worldwide in response to a spill 
expanded research into developing new technology for oil 
pollution control with 225 million allocated for three pilot 
research programs in california new york and along the gulf coast 
a requirement that the federal government check driving records 
for alcoholrelated offenses before allowing anyone to operate a 
tanker the captain of the exxon valdez had a history of 
alcoholrelated driving offenses and was accused of drinking before 
the alaska spill 
at the request of alaskas congressional delegation the bill 
would bar any tanker involved in an oil spill of more than 1 
million gallons from ever entering prince william sound 
alaska gov steve cowper praised the agreement saying 
congress is on the eve of charting a new course of environmental 
protection for the country congress should pass it as soon as 
possible to head off another disaster like the exxon valdez 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

