<TEXT>
after decades of business as usual the 
joint venture between chemical giant dupont and industry leader 
merck is the latest shakeup in an industry undergoing rapid change 
worldwide 
drug companies largely sat out the mergermad 1980s the 
industrys first major deal was in 1988 between two small danish 
firms novo and norodisk smithklinebeechman corp and marion 
merrell dow inc merged a short time later 
acquisitions became popular of late also ah robins was 
acquired by american home products corp hoffmannla roche 
acquired 60 percent of genentech and sterling drug co was bought 
by the film giant eastman kodak co 
there are other ways to work together without getting 
married said stuart levine of gruntal amp co who pointed to 
copromotion and codevelopment of products 
thats how merck and dupont got acquainted in october when 
merck obtained the rights to share in the development of a drug to 
reduce high blood pressure that dupont had originally patented 
that got the working relationship going said fred siemer 
an analyst who follows dupont for the chemical research inc 
the joint venture was planned with the longterm in mind 
according to p roy vagelos chief executive officer of merck the 
new companys research and development efforts are not expected to 
produce significant commercial results until the late 1990s 
like the merckdupont deal many of the recent mergers and 
acquisitions in the drug business have been driven at least partly 
by a desire to keep down research and development costs while 
gaining access to more markets 
wall street greeted the joint venture that was announced after 
the market closed wednesday dupont stock closed thursday at 40 
up 1 and merck closed at 89 up 
the dupont merck pharmaceuticals co will have a research and 
development staff of 1500 a sales staff of 600 and will spend 
230 million on research and development in its first year of 
existence 
dupont chipped in its entire pharmaceutical division while 
merck provides its research and development expertise marketing 
rights to several of its prescription medicines and cash and 
development funds 
analysts point to skyrocketing research and development costs 
when explaining all the activity in a field that had seen slow 
corporate change in the previous 30 years 
it takes a long time to invent your way into this business 
and its expensive siemer said 
the average cost of development of a drug from the time we 
set up a project to the time it comes out on the market is 230 
million vagelos said 
and levine pointed out that it once took from four to six years 
to develop a drug 
youre now looking at 12 or more years before bringing a drug 
to market he said 
it was duponts brisk rampd performance that attracted merck 
after dupont beat out merck and other firms in developing a new 
drug for high blood pressure company officials say 
and after spending all that time and money competition from 
generic drugs cut into sales once patents expire while pending 
patents provide a monopoly and a lock on profits 
generic competition comes on very rapidly once a patent 
expires said vagelos 
