<TEXT>
allied stores corp has received federal 
bankruptcy court approval of a unique borrowing arrangement to help 
the retailer continue operations through its chapter 11 
reorganization 
lawyers for allied said thursday the arrangement is a first in 
chapter 11 cases because it allows the company to obtain loan funds 
by selling shortterm corporate bonds on the market probably 
incurring lower interest rates than by borrowing from banks 
allied estimates the arrangement could save the company 10 
million a year in interest company lawyer david s kurtz told us 
bankruptcy judge j vincent aug jr 
the arrangement permits the company to borrow up to 630 
million which could be increased to 700 million if needed it is 
backed by the value of merchandise allied purchases with the 
borrowed funds and by a 105 million letter of credit from the 
french bank societe generale kurtz said 
we view this transaction as a major step forward in the 
reorganization and as a major achievement kurtz said 
kurtz said the arrangement also backed by chemical banking 
corp will last through may 1993 or if it occurs earlier the 
confirmation date of allieds financial reorganization plan which 
is yet to be filed the borrowing would permit allied to buy 
merchandise for its 126 stores in 17 states operated by its four 
merchandising divisions the bon inc jordan marsh stores corp 
sterns inc and maas inc 
the borrowing line replaces a 700 million credit line allied 
had obtained through citibank which was to expire july 31 kurtz 
said arrangements for the new credit would be concluded at a 
closing today in new york on monday allied will draw 386 million 
from the new borrowing line to pay off citibank kurtz said 
no creditors objected to the arrangement 
aug also approved a request by allied and its sister 
corporation federated department stores inc to allow federated 
to continue providing credit collection and related services to 
allied stores credit corp allieds credit arm 
federated and allied stores corp both owned by torontos 
