<DOCNO> AP900727-0193 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the slump in junk bond prices may have signaled 
an end to the corporate raiding of the 1980s but has given birth 
to a new breed of raider for the 1990s the bondmailer 
these investors seek out companies that have trouble making 
junkbond payments which depresses the value of the bonds the 
investors buy up a large chunk of the companys debt usually at a 
steep discount from face value 
then they offer management a choice either buy back the 
securities or face an involuntary bankruptcy petition 
a successful bondmailer chooses companies with bonds so 
undervalued in the market theyll return a profit even in a chapter 
11 bankruptcy reorganization once in bankruptcy court the 
bondmailers securities can bring cash or more likely equity in 
the company 
well see more and more of this in the 90s said c richard 
lehmann president of bond investors association inc a nonprofit 
miamibased firm that tracks bond defaults many companies will 
change hands through bond defaults and the substitution of credit 
instruments with stock 
the collapse of the junk bond market has left many companies 
struggling to make interest payments many of these highrisk 
securities feature whats known as a reset to make bondholders 
feel safer about their investment under a reset clause the bond 
issuer promises to raise the interest rate on the bond to increase 
its market value to par or face value 
with bond prices so depressed heavily indebted companies are 
faced with placing huge sometimes debilitating interest rates on 
their bonds some have to default on the issues 
in the first six months of the year the bond investors 
association recorded 40 bond defaults worth more than 11 billion 
that makes good hunting for a bondmailer 
earlier this year sci television inc avoided an involuntary 
bankruptcy petition filed by bond investor sn phelps amp co of 
greenwich conn the agreement gave 39 percent of the company to 
phelps and the other bondholders bank lenders got a 5 percent 
stake 
george gillett who had been controlling investor saw his stake 
drop from 55 percent to 41 percent kohlberg kravis roberts amp co 
which created sci through a debtfinanced takeover of storer 
communications in 1985 saw its interest drop from 45 percent to 15 
percent 
with the likelihood that bondholders will see their securities 
turn into stock through negotiations with management lehmann said 
chapter 11 filings could set off bidding wars 
the strategy is in some ways analogous to the greenmailers of 
the 1980s who bought large stakes of a companys stock then made 
nuisances of themselves by forcing restructurings or theatening 
takeovers until management gave them a profit for their stock 
not surprisingly the bondmailer label for the new form of 
raider is appearing to stick some have suggested the term 
vulture capitalist 
despite their pejorative nicknames these investors arent so bad 
in lehmanns eyes 
the trend were seeing is companies are squeezing bondholders 
by buying back bonds at a discount he said this keeps them 
honest besides even if a company capitulates to a bondmailers 
demands for a hefty profit on the debt the company is still 
retiring the bonds usually well below par 
by forcing a retirement of debt at a better price for 
bondholders the bondmailers are preempting what management 
itself should be doing lehmann said 
stanford phelps owner of phelps amp co has won widespread 
recognition in the popular press as a bondmailer by virtue of the 
current cover story in forbes magazine others however are hard at 
work also 
new yorkbased japonica partners for example is pressuring 
pittsbughbased appliance maker allegheny international 
if bond defaults and an undervalued junk bond market continue 
expect to see more of the bondmailers in the coming years 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
