usx corp has agreed to pay 34 million in costs 
and penalties for the cleanup of wastewater that was illegally 
dumped from its gary ind steel mill federal officials said today 
the agreement stems from a 1988 lawsuit filed by the federal 
government alleging that usx exceeded discharge limits in the grand 
calumet river the suit also alleged the company had made other 
violations of the federal clean water act 
under the agreement the company will pay 16 million in 
penalties and an estimated 25 million in cleanup and 
wastemanagement measures officials of the us environmental 
protection agency and the us attorneys office said 
the company also agreed to pay 25 million on a study to 
determine the extent of sediment contamination in the grand 
calumet located in northern indiana another 5 million will be 
allocated to clean up whatever contamination is found 
dale s bryson water division director for epas region 5 said 
todays settlement was among the top 10 in fines for illegal 
wastewater dumping but usx will pay more than any other company 
for actual cleanup measures he said 
in the lawsuit the epa contended that usx formerly us steel 
illegally bypassed its blast furnace wastewater treatment system 
dumping polluted water directly into the grand calumet and lake 
michigan on several occasions 
in september 1989 epa recommended that the usxgary works plant 
be suspended from doing business with the federal government 
