<TEXT>
usx corp will pay about 34 million in penalties 
and cleanup costs for dumping wastewater from its gary ind steel 
mill under an agreement announced friday by federal officials 
we believe this consent decree is a major victory for the 
muchabused grand calumet river said ralph r bauer deputy 
regional administrator for the us environmental protection 
agency we expect this decree to provide a framework for 
improvement and cleanup at the usx plant 
the outofcourt settlement resolves a 1988 lawsuit filed by the 
federal government alleging that the gary mill exceeded wastewater 
discharge limits in the river the lawsuit also alleged that the 
company violated the federal clean water act in other ways between 
1983 and 1988 
under the agreement announced by the epa and the us attorneys 
office for northern indiana the company will pay 16 million in 
civil penalties and an estimated 25 million to improve equipment 
and develop a comprehensive wastewater management plan 
the company has also agreed to pay 25 million on a study to 
determine the extent of sediment contamination in the grand calumet 
in northern indiana an additional 5 million will be allocated to 
clean up whatever contamination is found 
this is a consent decree said george kuebler a spokesman 
for usxs gary mill there are no admissions to any allegations 
the evidence that we are committed to the environment can be seen 
by agreeing to this decree which calls for spending beyond what is 
statutorily required 
dale s bryson of the regional epa office said the agreement 
ranks among the top 10 settlements ever received by the epa 
he said the 75 million the company will pay in total river 
cleanup costs is the highest amount ever negotiated specifically 
for that purpose 
bryson said the epa expects usx to complete the improvement 
efforts in two years 
the company could face additional penalties ranging from 750 
a day to 17500 a day for any missed deadlines bryson said 
in addition the epa must approve the companys cleanup and 
improvement plans and usx is obligated to pay the difference if 
costs exceed estimates made in the agreement he said 
in the lawsuit the epa contended that usx formerly us steel 
illegally bypassed its blast furnace wastewater treatment system 
dumping polluted water directly into the grand calumet and lake 
michigan on several occasions 
last september epa recommended that the usxgary works plant be 
suspended from doing business with the federal government because 
of the violations the agency will withdraw this recommendation 
once the decree has been entered in us district court in hammond 
officials said 
