<TEXT>
a former chicago mercantile exchange chairman 
facing possible expulsion from the futures industry said friday the 
british brokerage firm ed amp f man international futures inc was 
acquiring his commoditiestrading business 
brian monieson would not disclose the financial terms of the 
deal under which man will acquire on monday all assets customers 
and accounts of moniesons firm gnp commodities inc monieson said 
he will become a trader with man 
monieson gnps chairman is appealing to the commodities 
futures trading commission an administrative law judges may 25 
finding that he failed to adequately supervise two employees who 
defrauded customers 
monieson also is appealing to the federal regulatory agency the 
law judges order barring him from futures trading and requiring 
him to pay a 500000 fine 
the cftc administrative law judge also found chicagobased gnp 
commodities guilty of failing to adequately supervise the two 
employees and ordered the firm to close all customer accounts and 
pay a 500000 fine that finding also is being appealed 
monieson said in a telephone interview that he was selling the 
business basically to eliminate some of the uncertainty for our 
institutional customers because of the cftc proceedings 
monieson of northbrook ill was chairman of the merc the 
worlds secondlargest futures exchange from 1983 to 1985 
the fraudulent trading by the gnp employees occurred from 
september 1984 through may 1986 
</TEXT>
